There’s an Annunciation by Titian in the seven-domed cathedral (and a portrait attributed to him in the town museum). Treviso is proud of its links with Giotto’s follower Tommaso da Modena, and the Santa Caterina museum devotes a vaulted hall to his fresco cycle of the life of St Ursula. But for a taste of Tommaso’s humanity and humour, step into the modest Dominican chapter house of San Nicolò and look up at the frieze running round the walls – 40 portraits of Dominicans at their desks. One friar looks questioningly over his spectacles; his neighbour has his nose in a manuscript; another blows on a just-sharpened pencil.
